  <section class=3D"tex2jax_ignore mathjax_ignore" id=3D"the-gram-schmidt-p=
rocess">
<span id=3D"sec-gram-schmidt"></span><h1><span class=3D"section-number">7.3=
. </span>The Gram-Schmidt process<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://in=
teractivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#the-=
gram-schmidt-process" title=3D"Link to this heading">#</a></h1>
<section id=3D"introduction">
<h2><span class=3D"section-number">7.3.1. </span>Introduction<a class=3D"he=
aderlink" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Ch=
apter7/GramSchmidt.html#introduction" title=3D"Link to this heading">#</a><=
/h2>
<p>In <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.=
tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/OrthoBase.html#sec-orthobase"><span clas=
s=3D"std std-numref">Section 7.2</span></a> we have seen that orthogonal ba=
ses are nice to work with. Both for finding coordinates and also for findin=
g orthogonal projections.</p>
<p>In this section an algorithm is presented to construct an orthogonal bas=
is from an arbitrary basis of a subspace <span class=3D"math notranslate no=
highlight">\(W\)</span> in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\=
R^n\)</span>.</p>
<p>As a starter have a look at the following example</p>
<div class=3D"proof example admonition" id=3D"Ex:GramSchmidt:Example1">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Example 7.3.1 =
</span></p>
<section class=3D"example-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Let <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W\)</span> be the sub=
space in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\R^3\)</span> spann=
ed by the two vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{=
a}_1 =3D \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1   \\3    \end{pmatrix}\)</span> and <span c=
lass=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_2 =3D \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\=
 -2   \\1    \end{pmatrix}\)</span>.
We want to construct an orthogonal basis <span class=3D"math notranslate no=
highlight">\(\{\vect{b}_1,\vect{b}_2 \}\)</span> for <span class=3D"math no=
translate nohighlight">\(W\)</span>.</p>
<p>For the first vector of this =E2=80=98new=E2=80=99 basis we can simply t=
ake <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_1 =3D \vect{a}_=
1\)</span>.</p>
<p>As a second basis vector we can take</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight" id=3D"equation-eq-gramschmidt-s=
tep2">
<span class=3D"eqno">(7.3.1)<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://interac=
tivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#equation-=
eq-gramschmidt-step2" title=3D"Link to this equation">#</a></span>\[  \vect=
{b}_2 =3D \vect{a}_2 - \operatorname{proj}_{\vect{a}_1}(\vect{a}_2) =3D=20
               \vect{a}_2 - \dfrac{\vect{a}_2\ip\vect{a}_1}{\vect{a}_1\ip\v=
ect{a}_1}    \vect{a}_1.\]</div>
<p>It is then clear that <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\ve=
ct{b}_2\)</span> is in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\oper=
atorname{Span}\{\vect{a}_1, \vect{a}_2\}\)</span>, and by the property of t=
he orthogonal projection <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\op=
eratorname{proj}_{\vect{a}_1}(\vect{a}_2)\)</span> it follows that <span cl=
ass=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_2 \perp \vect{b}_1\)</span>=
.</p>
<p>A fortiori <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{b}_1, =
\vect{b}_2\}\)</span> is linearly independent, so <span class=3D"math notra=
nslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{b}_1, \vect{b}_2\}\)</span> is an orthogonal =
basis for <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W =3D \operatornam=
e{Span}{\{\vect{a}_1, \vect{a}_2\}}\)</span>.</p>
<p>The explicit vectors we find are</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
   \vect{b}_1 =3D \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1   \\3    \end{pmatrix}, \quad
   \vect{b}_2 =3D  \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ -2   \\1    \end{pmatrix} - \dfrac{=
7}{14}\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1   \\3    \end{pmatrix} =3D \begin{pmatrix} 2 \=
\ -5/2   \\ -1/2    \end{pmatrix} =3D
   \dfrac{1}{2}\begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -5   \\ -1    \end{pmatrix}.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>If we prefer vectors without fractions, we can rescale the second vector=
, and then find the orthogonal basis</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
  \{\vect{b}_1, 2\vect{b}_2\} =3D \left\{\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 1   \\3    \e=
nd{pmatrix},  \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ -5   \\ -1    \end{pmatrix}  \right\}.
\end{split}\]</div>
</section>
</div></section>
<section id=3D"id1">
<h2><span class=3D"section-number">7.3.2. </span>The Gram-Schmidt process<a=
 class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linea=
r-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#id1" title=3D"Link to this heading">#</=
a></h2>
<div style=3D"overflow:hidden;height:0px;margin:calc(var(--bs-body-font-siz=
e)*-0.5);"></div><div class=3D"proof theorem admonition" id=3D"Thm:GramSchm=
idt:GramSchmidt">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Theorem 7.3.1 =
</span></p>
<section class=3D"theorem-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Suppose <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W\)</span> is a s=
ubspace in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\R^n\)</span> wit=
h basis <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots,=
\vect{a}_m\}\)</span>. Construct the set of vectors
<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_1,\ldots,\vect{b}_m=
\)</span> according to the following rules</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}  \begin{array}{lcl}
     \vect{b}_1 &amp;=3D&amp; \vect{a}_1, \\
     \vect{b}_2 &amp;=3D&amp; \vect{a}_2 - \dfrac{\vect{a}_2\ip\vect{b}_1}{=
\vect{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1, \\
     \vect{b}_3 &amp;=3D&amp; \vect{a}_3 - \dfrac{\vect{a}_3\ip\vect{b}_1}{=
\vect{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1  - \dfrac{\vect{a}_3\ip\vect{b}_2}{\vect=
{b}_2\ip\vect{b}_2}\vect{b}_2 \\
  \end{array}
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>and in general</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[    \vect{b}_{j+1} =3D \vect{a}_{j+1} - \dfrac{\vect{a}_{j+1}\ip\vect{b}_=
1}{\vect{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1  - \cdots - \dfrac{\vect{a}_{j+1}\ip\=
vect{b}_j}{\vect{b}_j\ip\vect{b}_j}\vect{b}_j,
\]</div>
<p>for <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(j =3D 1,2,\ldots, m-1=
\)</span>.</p>
<p>Then all along the way</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\{\vect{b}_1, \ldots, \vect{b}_j\}
\]</div>
<p>is an orthogonal basis for</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\operatorname{Span}\{\vect{a}_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_j\}.
\]</div>
<p>In particular, in the end <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\=
(\{\vect{b}_1,\ldots,\vect{b}_m\}\)</span>
will be an orthogonal basis for <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight=
">\(\operatorname{Span}\{\vect{a}_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_m\} =3D W\)</span>.</=
p>
</section>
</div><p>The above construction/algorithm is called the <strong>Gram-Schmid=
t process</strong>.</p>
<div class=3D"proof example admonition" id=3D"Ex:GramSchmidt:Orthogonalize"=
>
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Example 7.3.2 =
</span></p>
<section class=3D"example-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Let <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W\)</span> be the def=
ined as the span of the set <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(=
\left\{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\ -1 \\ 1    \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix=
} 3 \\ 3   \\ -2 \\ 0    \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 1   \\ 4 \\ -4=
    \end{pmatrix}  \right\}\)</span>. It can be shown that these vectors ar=
e linearly independent.</p>
<p>We use the Gram-Schmidt algorithm to create an orthogonal basis for <spa=
n class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W\)</span>.</p>
<p>Step by step we find</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}  \vect{b}_1 =3D \vect{a}_1 =3D \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\-=
1  \\1  \end{pmatrix}, \quad
  \vect{b}_2 =3D \vect{a}_2 - \dfrac{\vect{a}_2\ip\vect{b}_1}{\vect{b}_1\ip=
\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1 =3D
  \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 3   \\-2  \\0  \end{pmatrix} -
  \dfrac{8}{4}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\-1  \\1  \end{pmatrix}=3D
  \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\0  \\-2  \end{pmatrix}
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>and</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}\begin{array}{lcl}
  \vect{b}_3 &amp;=3D&amp; \vect{a}_3 - \dfrac{\vect{a}_3\ip\vect{b}_1}{\ve=
ct{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1  - \dfrac{\vect{a}_3\ip\vect{b}_2}{\vect{b}=
_2\ip\vect{b}_2}\vect{b}_2 \\
  &amp;=3D&amp;
  \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 1   \\4  \\-4  \end{pmatrix} -
  \dfrac{-4}{4}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\-1  \\1  \end{pmatrix} -
  \dfrac{12}{6}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\0  \\-2  \end{pmatrix} =3D \begin=
{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0   \\3  \\1  \end{pmatrix}
  \end{array}
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>Check for yourself that the vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohi=
ghlight">\(\vect{b}_1,\vect{b}_2, \vect{b}_3\)</span> are indeed orthogonal=
.</p>
</section>
</div><div class=3D"tudproof admonition">
<p class=3D"admonition-title">Proof of <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSch=
midt.html#Thm:GramSchmidt:GramSchmidt">Theorem 7.3.1</a></p>
<p>Let <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</span> be the s=
ubspace spanned by the first <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\=
(j\)</span> vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}=
_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_j\)</span>, for <span class=3D"math notranslate nohigh=
light">\(j =3D 1,2\ldots,m\)</span>.</p>
<p>First of all</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[ \operatorname{Span}\{\vect{b}_1\} =3D W_1 =3D \operatorname{Span}\{\vect=
{a}_1\}.
\]</div>
<p>In the other steps, assume that we have so far created the orthogonal ba=
sis
<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{b}_1, \ldots,\vect{b=
}_j \}\)</span> for <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</s=
pan>.</p>
<p>Then in fact</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[ \vect{b}_{j+1} =3D \vect{a}_{j+1} - \operatorname{proj}_{W_j}(\vect{a}_{=
j+1}).
\]</div>
<p>Namely, the projection <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\o=
peratorname{proj}_{W_j}(\vect{a}_{j+1})\)</span> can be computed using the =
already created <em>orthogonal</em> basis
<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\((\vect{b}_1, \ldots, \vect{b=
}_j)\)</span> of <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</span=
>. See <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks=
.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#fig-gramschmidt-gs-ste=
p123"><span class=3D"std std-numref">Figure 7.3.1</span></a></p>
<figure class=3D"align-default" id=3D"fig-gramschmidt-gs-step123">
<img alt=3D"../_images/Fig-GramSchmidt-GS-step123.svg" class=3D"dark-light"=
 src=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/_images/Fig-=
GramSchmidt-GS-step123.svg">
<figcaption>
<p><span class=3D"caption-number">Fig. 7.3.1 </span><span class=3D"caption-=
text">First steps in the Gram-Schmidt process.</span><a class=3D"headerlink=
" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/G=
ramSchmidt.html#fig-gramschmidt-gs-step123" title=3D"Link to this image">#<=
/a></p>
</figcaption>
</figure>
<p>That is,</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[  \operatorname{proj}_{W_j}(\vect{a}_{j+1}) =3D
  \dfrac{\vect{a}_{j+1}\ip\vect{b}_1}{\vect{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1  +=
 \cdots + \dfrac{\vect{a}_{j+1}\ip\vect{b}_j}{\vect{b}_j\ip\vect{b}_j}\vect=
{b}_j.
\]</div>
<p>This makes <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\operatorname{=
proj}_{W_j}(\vect{a}_{j+1})\)</span>    an element of <span class=3D"math n=
otranslate nohighlight">\(W_{j}\)</span>  and
<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_{j+1} =3D \vect{a}_=
{j+1} - \operatorname{proj}_{W_j}(\vect{a}_{j+1})\)</span>  an element of
<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_{j+1}\)</span>.</p>
<p><span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_{j+1} \neq \vect=
{0}\)</span> since we assumed that the vectors <span class=3D"math notransl=
ate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_m\)</span> are independent,=
 so <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_{j+1}\)</span> =
is not in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</span>.</p>
<p>Moreover, <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_{j+1} =
=3D \vect{a}_{j+1} - \operatorname{proj}_{W_j}(\vect{a}_{j+1})\)</span> is =
perpendicular to <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</span=
> by the properties of orthogonal projection.
Since all <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_i\)</span=
> with <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(i \leq j\)</span> lie=
 in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</span>, this makes=
 <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_{j+1}\)</span> ort=
hogonal to all its predecessors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight=
">\(\vect{b}_1, \ldots, \vect{b}_j\)</span>.<br>
Hence if the vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b=
}_1, \ldots, \vect{b}_j\)</span> are orthogonal,
so are the vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_=
1, \ldots, \vect{b}_j, \vect{b}_{j+1}\)</span>.</p>
<p>(By using mathematical induction the proof can be made absolutely rigoro=
us.)</p>
</div>
