4"><div class=3D"description-container docutils container">
<p></p><p>Gram-Schmidt D.I.Y.</p>
<p></p>
</div>
</div>
<details class=3D"dropdown"><summary>&nbsp;Click to show/hide</summary><div=
 class=3D"grasplecontainer"><iframe loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"cid:frame-68F00=
9BE068F969E11B1EB69829A3ADE@mhtml.blink" class=3D"grasple dark-light"></ifr=
ame></div></details></section>
</div>
<p>The following example shows what happens if the Gram-Schmidt constructio=
n is applied to
a subspace <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W =3D \operatorna=
me{Span}\{\vect{a}_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_m\}\)</span> where the vectors <span=
 class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_i\)</span> are not linea=
rly independent.</p>
<div class=3D"proof example admonition" id=3D"Ex:GramSchmidt:NonOrthog">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Example 7.3.3 =
</span></p>
<section class=3D"example-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Let <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W\)</span> be the def=
ined as the span of the set <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(=
\left\{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -1   \\ 2 \\ 3    \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix=
} 2 \\ -2   \\ 4 \\ 6    \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0   \\ 1 \\  2=
    \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatrix} 0 \\ 2  \\ -3 \\  -4    \end{pmatrix} \r=
ight\}\)</span>.</p>
<p>Let us denote the vectors by <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight=
">\(\vect{a}_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_4\)</span>. As in the proof of the Gram-Sc=
hmidt process
we use the notation <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_j\)</s=
pan> for the span of the vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighligh=
t">\( \vect{a}_1, \ldots, \vect{a}_j\)</span>.</p>
<p>Just following the protocol we find</p>
<p><span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(
\)</span>\vect{b}_1 =3D \vect{a}<em>1 =3D \begin{pmatrix} 1 \ -1   \ 2 \ 3 =
   \end{pmatrix},  \quad
\vect{b}<em>2 =3D   \vect{a}</em>{2} - \dfrac{\vect{a}</em>{2}\ip\vect{b}_1=
}{\vect{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1        =3D \begin{pmatrix} 0 \ 0   \ 0=
 \ 0    \end{pmatrix}.
$$</p>
<p>The explanation is that <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\=
vect{b}_2 =3D \vect{a}_{2} - \operatorname{proj}_{\vect{a}_1}(\vect{a}_2) =
=3D
\vect{a}_{2} - \vect{a}_{2} =3D \vect{0}\)</span>, since <span class=3D"mat=
h notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_2\)</span> lies in <span class=3D"mat=
h notranslate nohighlight">\(\operatorname{Span}\{\vect{a}_1\}\)</span>.
In other words, since <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W_2 =
=3D W_1\)</span>.</p>
<p>We discard the zero vector, and continu to compute the next new basis ve=
ctor.</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
 \vect{b}_3 =3D \vect{a}_3 - \operatorname{proj}_{W_2}(\vect{a}_3) =3D \vec=
t{a}_3 - \operatorname{proj}_{W_1}(\vect{a}_3)
 =3D  \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0   \\ 1 \\  2    \end{pmatrix} - \dfrac{10}{15}=
\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -1   \\ 2 \\ 3    \end{pmatrix} =3D \dfrac13 \begin{pm=
atrix} 4 \\ 2   \\ -1 \\  0    \end{pmatrix}.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>To get rid of fractions we rather continue with <span class=3D"math notr=
anslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_3 =3D \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 2   \\ -1 \\  0 =
   \end{pmatrix}\)</span>.</p>
<p>The last step:</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[
  \vect{b}_4 =3D \vect{b}_4 - \operatorname{proj}_{\operatorname{Span}\{\ve=
ct{b}_1, \vect{b}_3\}}
             =3D \vect{b}_4 - \dfrac{-10}{15}\vect{b}_1 -\dfrac{7}{21}\vect=
{b}_3 =3D \vect{0}.
\]</div>
<p>Here again we may conclude that <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighli=
ght">\(\vect{a}_4\)</span> lies in <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighli=
ght">\(\operatorname{Span}\{\vect{b}_1,\vect{b}_3\}\)</span>, and we
discard <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{b}_4\)</span> =
from our basis.</p>
<p>The conclusion is that</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
 \left\{\vect{b}_1,\vect{b}_3\right\} =3D \left\{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ -1   =
\\ 2 \\ 3    \end{pmatrix},
          \begin{pmatrix} 4 \\ 2   \\ -1 \\ 0    \end{pmatrix}\right\}
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>is an orthogonal basis for <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">=
\(\operatorname{Span}\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots, \vect{a}_4\}\)</span>.</p>
</section>
</div><p>The idea of <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://intera=
ctivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#Ex:GramS=
chmidt:NonOrthog">Example 7.3.3</a> can be generalised as follows.
Suppose <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W =3D \operatorname{=
Span}\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots,\vect{a}_m\}\)</span>, where the vectors <span cla=
ss=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_i\)</span> are not
necessarily linearly independent.
If we apply the Gram-Schmidt construction and discard the zero vector if it=
 comes up, then we end up with an orthogonal basis <span class=3D"math notr=
anslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{b}_1,\ldots,\vect{b}_k\}\)</span> for <span =
class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W\)</span>. Note that <span class=
=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(k &lt; m\)</span> occurs precisely when=
 the original generating set of vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate noh=
ighlight">\(\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots,\vect{a}_m\}\)</span> is linearly dependent=
.</p>
<div class=3D"proof remark admonition" id=3D"Rem:GramSchmidt:OrthonormalBas=
is">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Remark 7.3.1 <=
/span></p>
<section class=3D"remark-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>By applying the Gram-Schmidt process to a linearly independent set of ve=
ctors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots,\v=
ect{a}_m\}\)</span> we get a orthogonal basis <span class=3D"math notransla=
te nohighlight">\(\{\vect{b}_1,\ldots,\vect{b}_m\}\)</span> for the subspac=
e <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(W =3D  \operatorname{Span}=
\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots,\vect{a}_m\}\)</span>.</p>
<p>By rescaling the vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(=
\vect{b}_i\)</span> as follows</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[   \vect{q}_i =3D \dfrac{\vect{b}_i }{\norm{\vect{b}_i}}, \quad  i =3D 1,=
 \ldots , m
\]</div>
<p>we can turn this new basis into an <strong>orthonormal</strong> basis.</=
p>
</section>
</div><div class=3D"proof example admonition" id=3D"Ex:GramSchmidt:Orthonor=
malize">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Example 7.3.4 =
</span></p>
<section class=3D"example-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>For the subspace</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}W =3D \operatorname{Span}
\left\{
    \begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\-1  \\1  \end{pmatrix},
    \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 3   \\-2  \\0  \end{pmatrix}
    \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ 1   \\4  \\-4  \end{pmatrix}
    \right\}.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>we found, in <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://interactive=
textbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#Ex:GramSchmid=
t:Orthogonalize">Example 7.3.2</a>, the orthogonal basis</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
   \left\{\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\-1  \\1   \end{pmatrix}, \begin{pmatri=
x} 1 \\ 1 \\0 \\-2  \end{pmatrix},   \begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0   \\3  \\1  \en=
d{pmatrix}\right\}.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>Rescaling (or normalising) gives the orthonormal basis</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}   \left\{ \dfrac{1}{2}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1   \\-1  \\1   =
\end{pmatrix}, \quad \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}}\begin{pmatrix} 1 \\ 1 \\0 \\-2  \e=
nd{pmatrix},   \quad  \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{14}}\begin{pmatrix} 2 \\ 0   \\3  \\1=
  \end{pmatrix}\right\}.
\end{split}\]</div>
</section>
</div><div class=3D"grasple fullscreenable admonition" id=3D"grasple_exerci=
se_7_3_B">

