<section id=3D"the-qr-decomposition">
<span id=3D"sec-gram-schmidt-qrdecomp"></span><h2><span class=3D"section-nu=
mber">7.3.3. </span>The <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(QR\)=
</span> decomposition<a class=3D"headerlink" href=3D"https://interactivetex=
tbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#the-qr-decomposi=
tion" title=3D"Link to this heading">#</a></h2>
<p>The Gram-Schmidt process leads to the following interesting decompositio=
n of an <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(n \times m\)</span>-=
matrix <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(A\)</span> with linea=
rly independent columns.</p>
<div style=3D"overflow:hidden;height:0px;margin:calc(var(--bs-body-font-siz=
e)*-0.5);"><p><span class=3D"target" id=3D"index-0"></span>$QR$ decompositi=
on</p>
</div><div class=3D"proof theorem admonition" id=3D"Thm:GramSchmidt:QR-deco=
mp">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Theorem 7.3.2 =
</span> (<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(QR\)</span> decompo=
sition)</p>
<section class=3D"theorem-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Suppose <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(A\)</span> is an =
<span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(n \times m\)</span>-matrix o=
f rank <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(m\)</span>.
Then <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(A\)</span> can be writt=
en as</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[   A =3D QR,
\]</div>
<p>where <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(Q\)</span> is an <s=
pan class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(n \times m\)</span>-matrix wit=
h <em>orthonormal columns</em>, and <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighl=
ight">\(R\)</span> is an <em>upper-triangular</em> <span class=3D"math notr=
anslate nohighlight">\(m \times m\)</span>-matrix, with <em>positive</em> d=
iagonal entries.</p>
<p>The matrix <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(Q\)</span> is =
found by applying the Gram-Schmidt process to the (linearly independent) co=
lumns <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect{a}_1,\ldots,\vec=
t{a}_m\)</span> of the matrix <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">=
\(A\)</span> and then renormalising.</p>
</section>
</div><div class=3D"tudproof admonition">
<p class=3D"admonition-title">Proof of <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSch=
midt.html#Thm:GramSchmidt:QR-decomp">Theorem 7.3.2</a></p>
<p>One way to see this, is to look at the creation of the orthonormal set <=
span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{q}_1,\ldots,\vect{q}_=
m\}\)</span>
from the linearly independent set <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlig=
ht">\(\{\vect{a}_1,\ldots,\vect{a}_m\}\)</span>.</p>
<p>The general step in the Gram-Schmidt process is of the form</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[ \vect{b}_{j+1} =3D \vect{a}_{j+1} - \dfrac{\vect{a}_{j+1}\ip\vect{b}_1}{=
\vect{b}_1\ip\vect{b}_1}\vect{b}_1  - \cdots - \dfrac{\vect{a}_{j+1}\ip\vec=
t{b}_j}{\vect{b}_j\ip\vect{b}_j}\vect{b}_j.
\]</div>
<p>Realising that each <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\vect=
{b}_i\)</span> is in the span
of <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\{\vect{a}_1, \vect{a}_2,=
 \ldots , \vect{a}_{i} \}\)</span>,</p>
<p>it follows that</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}  \begin{array}{ccl}
   \vect{b}_1 &amp;=3D&amp; \phantom{c_{12}}\vect{a}_1 \\
   \vect{b}_2 &amp;=3D&amp;   c_{12}\vect{a}_1 + \phantom{c_{23}}\vect{a}_2=
 \\
   \vect{b}_3 &amp;=3D&amp;   c_{13}\vect{a}_1 + c_{23}\vect{a}_2 + \vect{a=
}_3\\
    &amp; \vdots &amp;
  \end{array}
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>so</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}  B =3D (\vect{b}_1\,\,\vect{b}_2\,\,\cdots\,\,\vect{b}_m)  =
=3D
    (\vect{a}_1\,\,\vect{a}_2\,\,\cdots\,\,\vect{a}_m)
  \begin{pmatrix} 1 &amp; c_{12} &amp; c_{13} &amp; \cdots &amp; c_{1m} \\
  0 &amp; 1 &amp; c_{23} &amp; \cdots &amp; c_{2m} \\
  0 &amp; 0 &amp; 1 &amp; \cdots &amp; c_{3m} \\
  \vdots &amp; \vdots &amp;  &amp; \ddots &amp;  \\
  0 &amp; 0 &amp; 0 &amp; \cdots &amp; 1
   \end{pmatrix} =3D AC.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>Normalising the vectors <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(\=
vect{b}_i\)</span> can be seen as multiplying the matrix <span class=3D"mat=
h notranslate nohighlight">\(B\)</span> with a diagonal matrix <span class=
=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(D\)</span>:</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[   Q =3D (\vect{q}_1\,\,\vect{q}_2\,\,\cdots\,\,\vect{q}_m)  =3D  BD,
\]</div>
<p>where the diagonal entries <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">=
\(d_{ii}\)</span> of <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(D\)</sp=
an> are given by</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[    d_{ii} =3D \dfrac{1}{\norm{\vect{b}_i}}.
\]</div>
<p>So</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[  Q =3D BD =3D ACD =3D A(CD),
\]</div>
<p>where <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(CD\)</span> is an u=
pper-triangular matrix with positive diagonal entries.</p>
<p>Multiplying both sides with the inverse of <span class=3D"math notransla=
te nohighlight">\(CD\)</span> gives</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[  Q =3D A(CD) \iff A =3D Q(CD)^{-1} =3D QR,
\]</div>
<p>where <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(R =3D (CD)^{-1}\)</=
span> is still an upper-triangular matrix with positive diagonal entries.</=
p>
</div>
<p>There is an quicker way to find the matrix <span class=3D"math notransla=
te nohighlight">\(R\)</span> than by inverting the matrix <span class=3D"ma=
th notranslate nohighlight">\(CD\)</span> as in the proof of <a class=3D"re=
ference internal" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-al=
gebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#Thm:GramSchmidt:QR-decomp">Theorem 7.3.2</a=
>, which is the context of the next proposition.</p>
<div style=3D"overflow:hidden;height:0px;margin:calc(var(--bs-body-font-siz=
e)*-0.5);"></div><div class=3D"proof proposition admonition" id=3D"Prop:Gra=
mSchmidt:QR-quick">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Proposition 7.=
3.1 </span></p>
<section class=3D"proposition-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Let <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(Q =3D \begin{pmatrix}=
\vect{q}_1&amp;\cdots&amp;\vect{q}_m\end{pmatrix}\)</span> be the matrix co=
nstructed by exactly applying the Gram-Schmidt process followed by rescalin=
g. Define <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(R =3D Q^TA\)</span=
>.</p>
<p>Then <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(R\)</span> is an upp=
er-triangular matrix with a positive entries on its diagonal, and</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[  A =3D QR.
\]</div>
</section>
</div><div class=3D"tudproof admonition">
<p class=3D"admonition-title">Proof of <a class=3D"reference internal" href=
=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSch=
midt.html#Prop:GramSchmidt:QR-quick">Proposition 7.3.1</a></p>
<p>We know that for the matrix <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight"=
>\(Q\)</span> as specified the decomposition</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[  A =3D QR
\]</div>
<p>exists, with an upper-triangular matrix <span class=3D"math notranslate =
nohighlight">\(R\)</span>.</p>
<p>The matrix <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(Q\)</span> has=
 orthonormal columns, so</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[ Q^TQ =3D I.
\]</div>
<p>Thus we can retrieve <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(R\)<=
/span> if we multiply both sides of the equation <span class=3D"math notran=
slate nohighlight">\(\,A =3D QR\,\)</span> by <span class=3D"math notransla=
te nohighlight">\(\,Q^T\)</span>:</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[  A =3D QR  \quad \Longrightarrow \quad  Q^TA =3D Q^TQR =3D R.
\]</div>
</div>
<p>The following example provides an illustration of this last proposition.=
</p>
<div class=3D"proof example admonition" id=3D"Ex:GramSchmidt:AlternativePro=
ofQR">
<p class=3D"admonition-title"><span class=3D"caption-number">Example 7.3.5 =
</span></p>
<section class=3D"example-content" id=3D"proof-content">
<p>Consider the matrix</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
A=3D \begin{pmatrix}
  1 &amp; 3 &amp; 3\\
  1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1\\
  -1 &amp;-2 &amp; 4  \\
  1 &amp; 0 &amp;-4
\end{pmatrix}.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>From <a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://interactivetextbook=
s.tudelft.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#Ex:GramSchmidt:Orthog=
onalize">Example 7.3.2</a> and
<a class=3D"reference internal" href=3D"https://interactivetextbooks.tudelf=
t.nl/linear-algebra/Chapter7/GramSchmidt.html#Ex:GramSchmidt:Orthonormalize=
">Example 7.3.4</a>
we know that applying the Gram-Schmidt process to the columns of <span clas=
s=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(A\)</span>
leads to the matrix</p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
 Q =3D \begin{pmatrix}
        \dfrac{1}{2} &amp; \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}} &amp; \dfrac{2}{\sqrt{14}}\\
        \dfrac{1}{2} &amp; \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}} &amp; 0\\
        -\dfrac{1}{2} &amp; 0 &amp; \dfrac{3}{\sqrt{14}}\\
        \dfrac{1}{2} &amp;-\dfrac{2}{\sqrt{6}} &amp; \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{14}}
      \end{pmatrix}.
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>We compute <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(R =3D Q^TA\)</=
span></p>
<div class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">
\[\begin{split}
 \begin{pmatrix}
        \dfrac{1}{2} &amp; \dfrac{1}{2} &amp; -\dfrac{1}{2} &amp; \dfrac{1}=
{2} \\
        \dfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}} &amp;\dfrac{1}{\sqrt{6}} &amp;  0 &amp; -\dfrac=
{2}{\sqrt{6}} \\
        \dfrac{2}{\sqrt{14}} &amp; 0  &amp; \dfrac{3}{\sqrt{14}} &amp; \dfr=
ac{1}{\sqrt{14}}
      \end{pmatrix}
      \begin{pmatrix}  1 &amp; 3 &amp; 3\\
                       1 &amp; 3 &amp; 1\\
                      -1 &amp;-2 &amp; 4  \\
                       1 &amp; 0 &amp;-4 \end{pmatrix}
       =3D
      \begin{pmatrix}  2 &amp; 4 &amp; -2\\
                       0 &amp; \sqrt{6} &amp; 2\sqrt{6}\\
                       0 &amp; 0 &amp; \sqrt{14}  \end{pmatrix},
\end{split}\]</div>
<p>and see that this is indeed an upper-triangular matrix (with positive di=
agonal entries).</p>
<p>You may check for yourself that <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighli=
ght">\(QR =3D A\)</span>.</p>
</section>
</div><div class=3D"admonition warning">
<p class=3D"admonition-title">Warning</p>
<p>The columns of <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(Q\)</span>=
 being orthonormal is equivalent to <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighl=
ight">\(Q^TQ =3D I\)</span>. However, in the case where <span class=3D"math=
 notranslate nohighlight">\(Q\)</span> is not a square matrix, this does no=
t imply that <span class=3D"math notranslate nohighlight">\(QQ^T =3D I\)</s=
pan>.</p>
</div>
</section>
